While the argument is that it'll keep his seconds in command at their toes, it's hard to see him planning to step down, at least in practice. A name change is not out of the question though.

Vladimir Putin will not hold on to power forever, I believe there is a higher chance than many think that he will leave the position before 2022. Couple this emergency exit plan with Russia's increased reliance on the east, a strategy not believed to be favorable due to old fears of Chinese interests in Eastern Russia, and you have an interesting problem. Pro-Navalny protests have blackened Putin's "eye" permanently. Many factors sway my vote here, but I suspect Putin will not in power for long.

Putin controls the levers of the Russian state's power in terms of the largest political party, the military, and has a large majority of public support. It seems extremely unlikely that Putin would lose power in Russia except by sudden death, despite the fact he appears healthy and relatively young, or a very unexpected revolution. I don't believe that the chance of this occurring is quite 0% or 1% at this point, given historical examples of leaders dying in office over the course of 11 months and revolutions in general. The average rate of chiefs of state dying over the last 20 years in office is about 2.25 per year, which would imply about a 1% chance. With the additive chance of revolution from protests, which Russia has suffered two of over the last 105 years (2% per year). I would estimate a probability of about 3% all other things being equal. Given that Putin is slightly older than the average chief of state and protests are on-going from the jailing of Navalny I would bump that probability up slightly to 5%.

The stories referenced in this question point to interesting developments in the Russian political sphere - specifically, that Putin is rumored to have some health problems (Parkinson's?) and additionally, that he signed a bill late last year to give ex-presidents and their families lifetime immunity for crimes committed in their lifetimes. Putin seems to have no plans to leave office voluntarily until 2036 at the earliest.[1] This leads me to believe there is little chance he would leave of his own volition. The second, real question is whether we believe he will be driven from office by a popular revolt or a military coup. I find either outcome highly unlikely given Putin's iron grip on the military and security services. He also seems to enjoy enormous popularity with the Russian public, according to independent pollsters in Russia, who give him a current approval rating of 64%, a level that most Western democratic leaders can only envy.[2] This approval rating takes into account the domestic crackdown following the nationwide protests in support of opposition leader Alexei Navalny. The internationally peer-reviewed results on the Russian COVID vaccine, showing a 92% efficacy, also boost Putin's ability to remain in power long after January 2022.[3]
